# 1932 Democratic National Convention

The year 1932, a time when the [United States](/United_States) found itself in the suffocating grip of the [Great Depression](/Great_Depression), demanded more than just another political gathering. It required a convention that would not merely select a nominee but, perhaps, chart a course away from the precipice. The [1932 Democratic National Convention](/1932_Democratic_National_Convention), a pivotal moment in American political history, convened in the bustling, yet beleaguered, city of [Chicago](/Chicago), [Illinois](/Illinois). From June 27 to July 2, 1932, the [Chicago Stadium](/Chicago_Stadium) served as the crucible where the future of the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States))—and arguably, the nation—would be forged.

This assembly ultimately culminated in the nomination of [Governor](/List_of_Governors_of_New_York) [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt) of [New York](/New_York_(state)) for the presidency, a figure whose name would become synonymous with an era of profound transformation. Alongside him, for the crucial role of vice president, the delegates selected [Speaker of the House](/List_of_Speakers_of_the_United_States_House_of_Representatives) [John Nance Garner](/John_Nance_Garner) of [Texas](/Texas). Their ticket was poised to challenge the incumbent [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) administration, which many blamed for the nation's economic woes.

A notable, if often overlooked, moment of the convention involved [Beulah Rebecca Hooks Hannah Tingley](/Beulah_Rebecca_Hooks_Hannah_Tingley). As a distinguished member of the [Democratic National Committee](/Democratic_National_Committee) and the Chair of the [Democratic Party of Florida](/Democratic_Party_of_Florida), she held the distinct honor of seconding the nomination of [Franklin Delano Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt). This act marked her as only the second woman in the history of the [Democratic National Convention](/Democratic_National_Convention) to address the assembly, a subtle but significant step in an era still largely dominated by male voices. The convention, steeped in the hopeful rhetoric of change, adopted "[Happy Days Are Here Again](/Happy_Days_Are_Here_Again)" as its unofficial campaign anthem, a tune that would become indelibly linked with Roosevelt's ascendancy and the promise of a brighter future, as noted by the [White House Historical Association](/White_House_Historical_Association). This choice of song, in the depths of economic despair, was a masterstroke of political optimism, a stark contrast to the grim realities outside the convention hall.

## The Candidates

The political landscape leading up to the 1932 convention was dominated by a trio of formidable figures, each representing different currents within the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)). Their candidacies underscored the internal divisions and competing visions for how the party could reclaim the [White House](/White_House) and address the unprecedented challenges facing the country.

